  "prompt": "What are the goals of the Galileo global navigation satellite system?",
  "response": "The Galileo global navigation satellite system, developed by the European Union and European Space Agency, has several key goals:\n\n1. Provide independent satellite navigation for Europe\n- Reduce strategic dependence on GPS (United States) and GLONASS (Russia)\n- Ensure autonomous positioning and timing capabilities\n\n2. Deliver high-precision navigation services\n- Achieve greater accuracy for civilian and commercial applications\n- Provide more reliable positioning information\n\n3. Support multiple service levels\n- Open Service: Free basic navigation for general public\n- Commercial Service: Enhanced services for commercial applications\n- Public Regulated Service: Secure navigation for government entities\n- Search and Rescue Service: Contribute to global emergency location systems\n\n4. Enhance technological and economic competitiveness\n- Stimulate innovation in European satellite navigation technologies\n- Create economic opportunities in navigation-related industries\n\n5. Promote European technological independence\n- Develop indigenous satellite navigation infrastructure\n- Reduce reliance on foreign navigation systems\n\n6. Enable advanced technological applications\n- Support transportation, agriculture, emergency services\n- Facilitate precise timing and positioning for various sectors\n\n7. Improve global navigation satellite system interoperability\n- Ensure compatibility with other global navigation systems\n- Enable multi-constellation navigation capabilities\n\nThese goals collectively aim to strengthen Europe's technological capabilities and provide robust, accurate navigation services.",
